,\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Clarifying test changes**\\\\n\\\\nI might want to note that I didn’t make another test change because it’s impossible under JVM semantics. The latest relevant commit is e5a562525. Should I mention that the untracked file metadata/... is still there and untouched? It seems like mentioning that might be unnecessary. I’ll focus on crafting a clear yet concise explanation while keeping it informative enough. I’m eager to ensure everything is properly communicated!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"I investigated the remaining `resolveClass` call site, and there is no valid test-only way to reach it for `commons-io:commons-io:2.2`.\\n\\nWhy it is unreachable:\\n- The actual `2.2` bytecode is:\\n\\n```java\\nClass<?> clazz = Class.forName(name, false, classLoader);\\nif (clazz != null) {\\n    return clazz;\\n}\\nreturn super.resolveClass(objectStreamClass);\\n```\\n\\n- The call to `ObjectInputStream.resolveClass(...)` at line `75` is only taken if `Class.forName(...)` returns `null`.\\n- On the JVM, `Class.forName(String, boolean, ClassLoader)` does not return `null` for a missing class; it throws `ClassNotFoundException`.\\n- I also checked a pathological custom loader case: even if `loadClass(...)` returns `null`, `Class.forName(...)` still turns that into `ClassNotFoundException`, not `null`.\\n\\nSo for `2.2`:\\n- success path: returns the class\\n- failure path: throws `ClassNotFoundException`\\n- fallback path at line `75`: effectively unreachable\\n\\nWhat I already fixed:\\n- Updated the test to match real `2.2` behavior by asserting `ClassNotFoundException` instead of expecting fallback.\\n\\nCurrent test commit:\\n- `e5a562525` — `Adjust commons-io 2.2 class resolution test`\\n\\nConclusion:\\n- I do not recommend adding another test here, because it would not be able to cover that remaining call site without relying on impossible/non-JVM behavior.\\n- The dynamic-access report 